data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes `Func<>`, not `Expression<Func<>>`

Your manual expression tree building **won't compile** because `ExecuteUpdateAsync` now accepts a regular lambda. Replace the entire block with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. — the new API was designed specifically to eliminate that pain.

---

### 2. Complex type columns — two changes

**a) Sibling properties are now uniquified.** If `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously shared one `Street` column, EF 10 will generate `Street` and `Street1`. To preserve shared columns (or control names), be explicit:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** Your `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` column was previously `BillingAddress_City`; it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To keep the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

⚠️ Both changes affect **existing migrations**. Generate a new migration and inspect it — if you see column renames on production tables, pin old names with `HasColumnName` to avoid a destructive migration.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter. This carries the redacted SQL for logging (constants scrubbed unless `EnableSensitiveDataLogging` is on):

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the real SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** method signatures in your implementation — not just `CommandReaderExecuting`.
